# ===========================================
# Kvitt Mobile Environment
# Copy to .env and fill in your values.
# See docs/SETUP_KEYS.md for where to get each key.
# ===========================================

# Supabase Configuration
EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project.supabase.co
EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your-supabase-anon-key

# Backend API Configuration (production: kvitt.duckdns.org)
EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL=https://kvitt.duckdns.org/api
EXPO_PUBLIC_SOCKET_URL=https://kvitt.duckdns.org

# EAS project UUID (fixes "projectId: Invalid uuid" when registering for push notifications).
# Find it: https://expo.dev → your project → Project settings → Project ID.
# Optional if app.json extra.eas.projectId is set to the same UUID.
# EXPO_PUBLIC_EAS_PROJECT_ID=xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx

# Expo Go — `npx expo start --tunnel` (ngrok)
# Expo ships a shared ngrok token; when it hits limits (ERR_NGROK_108) the agent exits and you get
# connect ECONNREFUSED 127.0.0.1:4040. Fix: free account at ngrok.com, then set your token here (not EXPO_PUBLIC_):
# EXPO_NGROK_AUTHTOKEN=your_token_from_https://dashboard.ngrok.com/get-started/your-authtoken
# Or: npx ngrok config add-authtoken <token> (writes ~/.ngrok2/ngrok.yml) and still set EXPO_NGROK_AUTHTOKEN
# so Expo CLI uses it — postinstall patch reads this env (see scripts/patch-expo-cli-ngrok-authtoken.cjs).
# Kill stray ngrok.exe or anything on port 4040 if needed.
#
# If you see: ngrok tunnel took too long to connect — Expo’s default wait was 10s; this repo’s
# postinstall raises it to 60s (see scripts/patch-expo-cli-tunnel-timeout.cjs). For very slow links:
#   set EXPO_TUNNEL_TIMEOUT_MS=120000   (PowerShell: $env:EXPO_TUNNEL_TIMEOUT_MS=120000)
# Then `npm run start:tunnel`. Still failing: phone hotspot, `npx ngrok diagnose`, or IT allow
# *.ngrok.com. Android: `adb reverse tcp:8081 tcp:8081` + `npx expo start --localhost`.
